A cryptocurrency trading platform is using an API built in AWS Lambda and API Gateway. Due to the recent news and rumors about 
the upcoming price surge of Bitcoin, Ethereum and other cryptocurrencies, it is expected that the trading platform would have 
a significant increase in site visitors and new users in the coming days ahead.

In this scenario, how can you protect the backend systems of the platform from traffic spikes?

Move the Lambda function in a VPC.
Use CloudFront in front of the API Gateway to act as a cache.
Enable throttling limits and result caching in API Gateway.
Switch from using AWS Lambda and API Gateway to a more scalable and highly available architecture using EC2 instances, ELB, and Auto Scaling.



sol:

Using CloudFront in front of the API Gateway to act as a cache is incorrect because CloudFront only speeds up content delivery which provides
a better latency experience for your users. It does not help much for the backend.


✔ Throttling = Limits API requests per second to prevent overload. 🚦
✔ Caching = Stores API responses to reduce backend work. 📦

 What is Throttling? (Rate Limiting)
Throttling means controlling the number of requests an API can handle to prevent overload.

🔹 Example:
You set a limit of 1,000 requests per second for an API.
If the traffic suddenly spikes to 2,500 requests per second, API Gateway allows a short burst of 2,000 requests per second but blocks anything beyond that.
The blocked requests get a 429 (Too Many Requests) error.
API Gateway automatically retries failed requests to smooth out traffic.

✅ Why is Throttling Important?
Prevents overloading of servers.
Stops abuse (e.g., bot attacks).
Ensures fair usage of API resources.


