A company has an AWS Direct Connect connection from its on-premises location to an AWS account. The AWS account has 30 different VPCs 
in the same AWS Region. The VPCs use private virtual interfaces (VIFs). Each VPC has a CIDR block that does
not overlap with other networks under the company's control.

The company wants to centrally manage the networking architecture while still allowing each VPC to communicate with all other VPCs and on-premises networks.

Which solution will meet these requirements with the LEAST amount of operational overhead?

A. Create a transit gateway, and associate the Direct Connect connection with a new transit VIF. Turn on the transit 
gateway's route propagation feature. Most Voted
B. Create a Direct Connect gateway. Recreate the private VIFs to use the new gateway. Associate each VPC by 
creating new virtual private gateways.
C. Create a transit VPConnect the Direct Connect connection to the transit VPCreate a peering connection between all 
other VPCs in the Region. Update the route tables.
D. Create AWS Site-to-Site VPN connections from on premises to each VPC. Ensure that both VPN tunnels are UP for
each connection. Turn on the route propagation feature.

ans:

A. Create a transit gateway, and associate the Direct Connect connection with a new transit VIF. Turn on 
the transit gateway's route propagation feature.
Transit Gateway is a central hub for VPC networking, enabling inter-VPC communication without complex peering or managing routes manually.
Direct Connect with Transit VIF: You would associate the Direct Connect connection with a new transit virtual interface (VIF) to
allow the on-premises network to communicate with the transit gateway.
Route Propagation: By enabling route propagation on the transit gateway, routes between all VPCs and the on-premises 
network are automatically updated in each VPC's route table.

Why is this the best option?

The Transit Gateway simplifies the routing architecture by allowing centralized communication between all VPCs and the on-premises network.
Minimal operational overhead: Once the transit gateway is set up, all VPCs are automatically connected to each other and the on-premises network, 
and routes are automatically propagated.
It scales well as new VPCs are added, since you don't need to modify individual VPC route tables or manage a complex network of peering connections.


B. Create a Direct Connect gateway. Recreate the private VIFs to use the new gateway. Associate each VPC by creating new virtual private gateways.
Direct Connect Gateway allows you to connect multiple VPCs (in the same or different regions) to a Direct Connect connection.
However, for each VPC, you'd need to create a new virtual private gateway and associate it with the Direct Connect gateway. This means you'll have to set
up multiple private virtual interfaces and
ensure each VPC has its own VPN connection.

Why this isn't the best option:
It requires more manual setup for each VPC (creating VPGs and updating routing) compared to a Transit Gateway.
Higher operational overhead: You need to manage connections for each VPC separately, which increases complexity as the number of VPCs grows.
Scaling is harder: Adding new VPCs requires creating new virtual private gateways and modifying the route tables.


C. Create a transit VPC. Connect the Direct Connect connection to the transit VPC. Create a peering connection between all other 
VPCs in the region. Update the route tables.
A transit VPC is a solution where you create a VPC that acts as a hub for routing traffic to other VPCs. You would then create
VPC peering between the transit VPC and the other VPCs.
You'd also need to manually manage route tables to ensure communication between VPCs and the on-premises network.

Why this isn't the best option:
Manual peering between every VPC adds significant complexity. As the number of VPCs grows, the number of
peering connections increases, which becomes hard to maintain.
This approach is less scalable and requires more manual route table management.
Higher operational overhead, especially as more VPCs and resources are added.

D. Create AWS Site-to-Site VPN connections from on-premises to each VPC. Ensure that both VPN tunnels are
UP for each connection. Turn on the route propagation feature.
This option involves creating individual Site-to-Site VPN connections from your on-premises network to each VPC.
Each VPC would need a dedicated VPN connection, and you'd enable route propagation to automatically update routes.

Why this isn’t ideal:
VPN connections are useful but come with higher operational overhead: Managing 30 Site-to-Site VPNs would be complex and time-consuming.
Scalability becomes difficult as the number of VPCs grows.
This option would increase costs and add complexity to your network architecture compared to other options.




----------------------
63. A company is building an ecommerce application and needs to store sensitive customer information. The company needs to give customers the ability to complete
purchase transactions on the website. The company also needs to ensure that sensitive customer data is protected, even from database administrators.

Which solution meets these requirements?

A. Store sensitive data in an Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS) volume. Use EBS encryption to encrypt the data. Use an IAM instance role to restrict access.
B. Store sensitive data in Amazon RDS for MySQL. Use AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) client-side encryption to encrypt the data. Most Voted
C. Store sensitive data in Amazon S3. Use AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) server-side encryption to encrypt the data. Use S3 bucket policies to restrict access.
D. Store sensitive data in Amazon FSx for Windows Server. Mount the file share on application servers. Use Windows file permissions to restrict access.


sol: 
RDS MySQL provides a fully managed database service well suited for an ecommerce application.
AWS KMS client-side encryption allows encrypting sensitive data before it hits the database. The data remains encrypted at rest.
This protects sensitive customer data from database admins and privileged users.
EBS encryption (Option A) protects data at rest but not in use. IAM roles don't prevent admin access.
>>>S3 (Option C) encrypts data at rest on the server side. Bucket policies don't restrict admin access.
FSx file permissions (Option D) don't prevent admin access to unencrypted data.



