A company operates a two-tier application for image processing. The application uses two Availability Zones, each with one public subnet and one private
subnet. An Application Load Balancer (ALB) for the web tier uses the public subnets. Amazon EC2 instances for the application tier use the private subnets.

Users report that the application is running more slowly than expected. A security audit of the web server log files shows that the application is 
receiving millions of illegitimate requests from a small number of IP addresses. A solutions architect needs to resolve the immediate performance
problem while the company investigates a more permanent solution.

What should the solutions architect recommend to meet this requirement?

A. Modify the inbound security group for the web tier. Add a deny rule for the IP addresses that are consuming resources.
B. Modify the network ACL for the web tier subnets. Add an inbound deny rule for the IP addresses that are consuming resources. Most Voted
C. Modify the inbound security group for the application tier. Add a deny rule for the IP addresses that are consuming resources.
D. Modify the network ACL for the application tier subnets. Add an inbound deny rule for the IP addresses that are consuming resources.


A: Wrong as SG cannot deny. By default everything is deny in SG and you allow stuff
CD: App tier is not under attack so these are irrelevant options
B: Correct as NACL is exactly for this access control list to define rules for CIDR or IP addresses



***********
Security Groups (SG)
Purpose:
Security Groups act as virtual firewalls for EC2 instances. They control which inbound and outbound traffic is allowed to reach your EC2 instances.
Key Characteristics:
Stateful: If you allow inbound traffic, the response (outbound) is automatically allowed, even if there is no outbound rule for it.
Level: Applied at the instance level. Each EC2 instance can have multiple security groups.
Rule Type: Can only allow traffic. Cannot block traffic; if a traffic type is not allowed by any rule, it is implicitly denied.



Network Access Control Lists (NACLs)
Purpose:
Network ACLs are used to control traffic at the subnet level. They allow you to specify rules for both inbound 
and outbound traffic and apply to all resources within a subnet.

Key Characteristics:
Stateless: You must explicitly define both inbound and outbound rules. Traffic will not be automatically allowed to return (like in SGs). 
You need both rules to allow two-way communication.
Level: Applied at the subnet level. A single NACL affects all resources in a subnet (like EC2, RDS, etc.).
Rule Type: Can both allow and deny traffic, providing finer control over which traffic is blocked.
Default Behavior: By default, new NACLs allow all inbound and outbound traffic unless modified. You can configure deny rules to block unwanted traffic.
Effect on Subnet: NACLs are useful to create security boundaries between subnets.

When to Use:
Use NACLs when you want to block specific types of traffic (using deny rules) or control the flow of traffic at the subnet level (e.g., between public and private subnets).




Route Table (RT)
Purpose:
Route Tables control where traffic is directed within a VPC. They are responsible for determining the next hop for network traffic.

Key Characteristics:
Defines traffic flow: Determines where traffic should go based on destination IP addresses.
Level: Works at the subnet level and applies to all resources within the subnet.
State: It is stateless, meaning no memory of previous requests. For every new request, it needs to check the route.
Default Routes: Usually has a default route (0.0.0.0/0) that directs traffic to an Internet Gateway (IGW), NAT Gateway, or VPN Gateway.
No Allow/Deny Rules: Route tables don't allow you to specify rules to allow or deny traffic; they simply determine the direction of traffic.

When to Use:
Use route tables when you need to control the network traffic direction. For example, route traffic from a private subnet through a NAT 
Gateway or route traffic from the public subnet through an Internet Gateway.


Comparison of Route Tables, Security Groups, and NACLs
Feature	     Route Table	                                    Security Group (SG)	                                 Network ACL (NACL)
Purpose	     Controls traffic routing (where traffic goes)	   Controls traffic access(whocan access EC2instances)	Controls traffic access (subnet-level rules for traffic flow)
Level	        Subnet-level (affects all resources in subnet)	Instance-level (EC2 instances)	                     Subnet-level (affects all resources in subnet)
Statefulness  Stateless (doesn’t remember previous requests)	Stateful (allows return traffic automatically)	      Stateless (requires explicit inbound and outbound rules)
Rule Type	  Routes traffic to specific destinations	         Allow only (cannot block traffic)	                  Allow and Deny traffic
Deflt Behavr  Routes traffic based on destination IP	         Denies all inbound traffic by default	               Allows all inbound and outbound traffic by default
Direction	  Inbound and outbound traffic                     routingInbound and outbound (ingress n egress)rules	Inbound and outbound (ingress and egress) rules
Usage	        Used to control where traffic should go(next hop)	Used to control access to EC2 instances	         Used to control traffic flow between subnets, or VPCs

**************************




