A company’s applications use Apache Hadoop and Apache Spark to process data on premises. The existing infrastructure is not scalable and is complex to manage.

A solutions architect must design a scalable solution that reduces operational complexity. The solution must keep the data processing on premises.

Which solution will meet these requirements?

A. Use AWS Site-to-Site VPN to access the on-premises Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS) data and application. Use an Amazon EMR cluster to process the data.
B. Use AWS DataSync to connect to the on-premises Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS) cluster. Create an Amazon EMR cluster to process the data.
C. Migrate the Apache Hadoop application and the Apache Spark application to Amazon EMR clusters on AWS Outposts. Use the EMR clusters to process the data. Most Voted
D. Use an AWS Snowball device to migrate the data to an Amazon S3 bucket. Create an Amazon EMR cluster to process the data.


C cover requirement: The solution must keep the data processing on premises




AWS Outposts
AWS Outposts is a fully managed service that extends AWS infrastructure, services, and tools to on-premises data centers or edge locations.
It allows businesses to run AWS services locally while maintaining seamless integration with the AWS Cloud.


How It Works (Step-by-Step)

Order an AWS Outposts Rack
Customers choose an Outposts configuration (compute, storage, networking) based on their workload requirements.
AWS ships and installs a fully pre-configured rack to the customer’s on-premises location.

Installation & Connectivity
The Outposts rack is physically installed in the data center.
It connects to the AWS Cloud via a Direct Connect or VPN link.
AWS manages updates, monitoring, and maintenance remotely.

Deploy & Run AWS Services Locally
Customers can launch AWS services (EC2, EBS, RDS, S3, EMR, etc.) on-premises just like they do in the AWS Cloud.
The Outposts rack integrates with AWS IAM, VPC, and Security Groups for consistent security and access control.

Data Processing & Hybrid Cloud Integration
Workloads running on Outposts can interact with AWS Cloud services (e.g., backup to Amazon S3, machine learning with SageMaker).
Low-latency applications process data on-site, reducing data transfer delays to the cloud.

🔑 Key Features of AWS Outposts
✅ Hybrid Cloud Solution – Run AWS workloads on-premises with direct connectivity to AWS Cloud.
✅ Fully Managed by AWS – AWS takes care of updates, patching, and maintenance.
✅ Low Latency – Ideal for applications that require real-time data processing close to the source.
✅ Supports AWS Services – Can run Amazon EC2, Amazon S3, Amazon EMR, RDS, EKS, Lambda, and more.
✅ Connected to AWS – Integrates with AWS services like Amazon S3, Amazon VPC, and AWS IAM.

📌 Use Cases for AWS Outposts
Big Data & Analytics – Run Apache Hadoop, Apache Spark, or Amazon EMR on-premises for low-latency data processing.
Machine Learning (ML) & AI – Process large datasets close to the data source.
Edge Computing – Handle workloads in factories, hospitals, retail stores, or oil rigs where real-time processing is needed.
Regulated Industries – Useful for banking, healthcare, and government sectors that require on-premises data residency.

📌 Best Answer to Your Question
Since the company wants to keep data processing on-premises, the best option is:
✅ C. Migrate the Apache Hadoop and Apache Spark applications to Amazon EMR clusters on AWS Outposts. Use the EMR clusters to process the data.

💡 Why?
Maintains on-premises data processing ✅
Scales easily using AWS-managed infrastructure ✅
Reduces operational complexity ✅


