A company is designing a new web service that will run on Amazon EC2 instances behind an Elastic Load Balancing (ELB) load balancer. 
However, many of the web service clients can only reach IP addresses authorized on their firewalls.

What should a solutions architect recommend to meet the clients’ needs?

A. A Network Load Balancer with an associated Elastic IP address. Most Voted
B. An Application Load Balancer with an associated Elastic IP address.
C. An A record in an Amazon Route 53 hosted zone pointing to an Elastic IP address.
D. An EC2 instance with a public IP address running as a proxy in front of the load balancer.

Understanding the Problem
The company is running a web service on Amazon EC2 instances behind a load balancer (ELB).
Some clients can only access specific, pre-approved IP addresses because their firewalls block unknown IPs.
ELB does not have a fixed IP address (except for one type).
The solution needs to provide a stable, authorized IP so that the clients can access the web service without being blocked.

sol:
A for sure. The same question was in "AWS Certified Solutions Architect Associate Practice Test 3" on Udemy. There was an explaination 
that NLB needs to be before ALB because only NLB can have static IP.


