A company sets up an organization in AWS Organizations that contains 10 AWS accounts. A solutions architect must design a solution to
provide access to the accounts for several thousand employees. The company has an existing identity provider (IdP). The company 
wants to use the existing IdP for authentication to AWS.

Which solution will meet these requirements?

A. Create IAM users for the employees in the required AWS accounts. Connect IAM users to the existing IdP. Configure
federated authentication for the IAM users.
B. Set up AWS account root users with user email addresses and passwords that are synchronized from the existing IdP.
C. Configure AWS IAM Identity Center (AWS Single Sign-On). Connect IAM Identity Center to the existing IdP. Provision users 
and groups from the existing IdP.
D. Use AWS Resource Access Manager (AWS RAM) to share access to the AWS accounts with the users in the existing IdP.



sol:

The company has 10 AWS accounts under AWS Organizations.
There are thousands of employees who need access.
The company already has an Identity Provider (IdP) (e.g., Microsoft Active Directory, Okta, Google Workspace).
They want to use the existing IdP for authentication instead of manually creating AWS credentials.

Best Solution: AWS IAM Identity Center (AWS SSO)
✅ Correct Answer: C. Configure AWS IAM Identity Center (AWS Single Sign-On). Connect IAM Identity Center to the existing IdP. Provision users and groups from the existing IdP.

👉 Why?
AWS IAM Identity Center (AWS SSO) allows organizations to:
Connect AWS accounts with an external IdP (like Okta, Microsoft AD, or Google).
Let employees log in once using their company credentials and access multiple AWS accounts.
Automatically manage user permissions via groups and roles.

How AWS IAM Identity Center (AWS SSO) Works
Set up AWS IAM Identity Center (AWS SSO) in AWS Organizations.
Connect AWS IAM Identity Center to the company's IdP using SAML 2.0 integration.
Sync users & groups from the IdP into AWS IAM Identity Center.
Assign access permissions to AWS accounts using groups (e.g., Admins get full access, Developers get limited access).
Users log in once with their existing credentials and can switch between AWS accounts without re-entering passwords.

Why the Other Options Are Wrong?
Option                                                                	Why It's Wrong?
A. Create IAM users for emp & configure federated authencatn	❌ Not scalable for thousands of employees. Manually managing IAM users across 10 AWS accounts is inefficient.
B. Use AWS root users with emails & passwords from the IdP	    ❌ Root users are for account ownership, not daily operations. Using root users for access control is insecure.
D. Use AWS Resource Access Manager (AWS RAM) to share access	 ❌ AWS RAM is for sharing resources (e.g., VPCs, Subnets) between accounts, not for authentication.

