A company wants to configure its Amazon CloudFront distribution to use SSL/TLS certificates. The company does not want to use the default domain
name for the distribution. Instead, the company wants to use a different domain name for the distribution.

Which solution will deploy the certificate without incurring any additional costs?

A. Request an Amazon issued private certificate from AWS Certificate Manager (ACM) in the us-east-1 Region.
B. Request an Amazon issued private certificate from AWS Certificate Manager (ACM) in the us-west-1 Region.
C. Request an Amazon issued public certificate from AWS Certificate Manager (ACM) in the us-east-1 Region.
D. Request an Amazon issued public certificate from AWS Certificate Manager (ACM) in the us-west-1 Region


CloudFront serves content to public users over the internet.

Public SSL/TLS certificates are trusted by browsers and allow secure HTTPS communication between users and CloudFront.
Private SSL/TLS certificates are used for internal applications within a private network (e.g., internal services in a VPC).
They are not trusted by browsers and require AWS Private CA, which incurs costs.
CC IS THE ANS
THE CERTIFICATES ARE HOSTED IN EAST US_EAST_1


