A company has primary and secondary data centers that are 500 miles (804.7 km) apart and interconnected with high-speed fiber-optic cable. The company
needs a highly available and secure network connection between its data centers and a VPC on AWS for a mission-critical workload. A solutions architect must
choose a connection solution that provides maximum resiliency.

Which solution meets these requirements?

A. Two AWS Direct Connect connections from the primary data center terminating at two Direct Connect locations on two separate devices
B. A single AWS Direct Connect connection from each of the primary and secondary data centers terminating at one Direct Connect location on the same device
C. Two AWS Direct Connect connections from each of the primary and secondary data centers terminating at two Direct Connect locations on two separate devices 
D. A single AWS Direct Connect connection from each of the primary and secondary data centers terminating at one Direct Connect location on two separate devices


A. Two DX connections from the primary data center to two DX locations ❌ Incorrect	
No redundancy for the secondary data center. If the primary data center fails, there's no backup path.
B. Single DX connection from each data center to one DX location, same device	❌ Incorrect	
Single DX location and same device create a single point of failure.
C. Two DX connections from each data center to two DX locations, separate devices ✅ Correct
Best redundancy – multiple paths, multiple locations, and multiple devices.
D. Single DX connection from each data center to one DX location, different devices	❌ Incorrect	
One DX location is a risk – failure at this location disconnects both data centers.



