A company runs many workloads on AWS and uses AWS Organizations to manage its accounts. The workloads are hosted on Amazon EC2, AWS Fargate, and
AWS Lambda. Some of the workloads have unpredictable demand. Accounts record high usage in some months and low usage in other months.
The company wants to optimize its compute costs over the next 3 years. A solutions architect obtains a 6-month average for each of the accounts
across the organization to calculate usage.
Which solution will provide the MOST cost savings for all the organization's compute usage?

A. Purchase Reserved Instances for the organization to match the size and number of the most common EC2 instances from the member accounts.
B. Purchase a Compute Savings Plan for the organization from the management account by using the recommendation at the management account level.
C. Purchase Reserved Instances for each member account that had high EC2 usage according to the data from the last 6 months.
D. Purchase an EC2 Instance Savings Plan for each member account from the management account based on EC2 usage data from the last 6 months.

ans:

A Compute Savings Plan provides the most flexibility and highest cost savings across Amazon EC2, AWS Lambda, and AWS Fargate,
which are the services used by the company.

Covers multiple services: Unlike Reserved Instances, Compute Savings Plans apply to EC2 (any instance type), Fargate, and Lambda.
Applies organization-wide: Since the company uses AWS Organizations, purchasing a Compute Savings Plan at the management account level allows
all member accounts to benefit.
Handles unpredictable demand: Because usage varies from month to month, Compute Savings Plans adapt better than Reserved Instances.
Optimized over 3 years: AWS provides recommendations at the management account level to maximize savings.

Why Not the Other Options?
❌ A (Purchase Reserved Instances for EC2 instances in member accounts)
Limited to EC2 only (does not cover Lambda or Fargate).
Reserved Instances lack flexibility if demand shifts to different instance types, sizes, or regions.

❌ C (Purchase Reserved Instances for high-usage EC2 accounts)
Similar issue as A—only covers EC2, and does not adjust well to demand fluctuations.
If accounts' usage changes, RIs may not provide savings.

❌ D (EC2 Instance Savings Plan for each account)
EC2 Instance Savings Plan is too restrictive compared to Compute Savings Plan.
This plan is specific to EC2 instances, while Compute Savings Plan covers EC2, Fargate, and Lambda.
Not optimal for organization-wide cost management because each account would have to manage its own plan.

