A company wants to isolate its workloads by creating an AWS account for each workload. The company needs a solution that centrally manages
networking components for the workloads. The solution also must create accounts with automatic security controls (guardrails).

Which solution will meet these requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?

A. Use AWS Control Tower to deploy accounts. Create a networking account that has a VPC with private subnets and public subnets.
Use AWS Resource Access Manager (AWS RAM) to share the subnets with the workload accounts. 
B. Use AWS Organizations to deploy accounts. Create a networking account that has a VPC with private subnets and public subnets.
Use AWS Resource Access Manager (AWS RAM) to share the subnets with the workload accounts.
C. Use AWS Control Tower to deploy accounts. Deploy a VPC in each workload account. Configure each VPC to route through an inspection VPC by using a transit gateway attachment.
D. Use AWS Organizations to deploy accounts. Deploy a VPC in each workload account. Configure each VPC to route through an inspection VPC by using a transit gateway attachment.



sol:

Why A?
This solution provides centralized networking management and automated security controls with the least operational overhead by
leveraging AWS Control Tower and AWS Resource Access Manager (AWS RAM).

AWS Control Tower helps centrally manage and automate the creation of AWS accounts while applying security guardrails.
A separate networking account keeps networking components centralized and isolated from workloads.
AWS Resource Access Manager (AWS RAM) allows subnets and networking resources to be shared with workload accounts, reducing duplication and operational complexity.
This setup ensures standardized security policies across accounts and improves network management efficiency.
Why Not the Other Options?

❌ B. Use AWS Organizations to deploy accounts and share subnets with AWS RAM
AWS Organizations alone does not automate security guardrails like AWS Control Tower does.
Would require manual security setup and account creation, leading to more operational overhead.

❌ C. Use AWS Control Tower, deploy a VPC in each workload account, and use a transit gateway for routing
More complex networking setup (each account gets a VPC and routes through a central inspection VPC).
More operational overhead compared to centrally managing the network in one networking account.
Using AWS RAM to share subnets (Option A) is a simpler and more scalable approach.

❌ D. Use AWS Organizations, deploy a VPC in each workload account, and use a transit gateway
Same issues as C (complex networking with a transit gateway).
No automated security guardrails—AWS Control Tower is better for security automation.
Requires more manual setup and management, increasing overhead.



AWS Resource Access Manager (AWS RAM)

AWS Resource Access Manager (AWS RAM) is a service that allows you to share AWS resources across multiple AWS accounts within an AWS Organization or with specific AWS accounts.
Key Features of AWS RAM:
✅ Centralized Resource Sharing – Share resources from one account (e.g., a networking account) with other accounts.
✅ Supports AWS Organizations – Can automatically share resources with all accounts in an AWS Organization.
✅ Eliminates Duplication – Instead of creating the same resources in multiple accounts, share them to reduce costs and complexity.
✅ Access Control – Uses IAM policies to define which accounts can access shared resources.
Common Use Cases
1️⃣ Centralized Networking: Share VPC subnets, Transit Gateways, or Route53 resolver rules with multiple AWS accounts.
2️⃣ Shared License Management: Share AWS License Manager configurations for managing software licenses across accounts.
3️⃣ Storage Sharing: Share AWS Backup vaults or FSx file systems across accounts.
4️⃣ Centralized Data Access: Share Amazon Aurora databases or Amazon S3 Access Points securely between accounts.


