A software company needs to upgrade a critical web application. The application currently runs on a single Amazon EC2 instance that the company hosts in a public subnet.
The EC2 instance runs a MySQL database. The application's DNS records are published in an Amazon Route 53 zone.

A solutions architect must reconfigure the application to be scalable and highly available. The solutions architect must also reduce MySQL read latency.

Which combination of solutions will meet these requirements? (Choose two.)

A. Launch a second EC2 instance in a second AWS Region. Use a Route 53 failover routing policy to redirect the traffic to the second EC2 instance.
B. Create and configure an Auto Scaling group to launch private EC2 instances in multiple Availability Zones. Add the instances to a target group behind
a new Application Load Balancer. Most Voted
C. Migrate the database to an Amazon Aurora MySQL cluster. Create the primary DB instance and reader DB instance in separate Availability Zones. Most Voted
D. Create and configure an Auto Scaling group to launch private EC2 instances in multiple AWS Regions. Add the instances to a target
group behind a new Application Load Balancer.
E. Migrate the database to an Amazon Aurora MySQL cluster with cross-Region read replicas.


sol:
B and E. Migrate the database to an Amazon Aurora MySQL cluster with cross-Region read replicas.
Cross-Region read replicas add significant latency for read requests, which is the opposite of what is needed to reduce read latency.
-----------------------------



A company is using an Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (Amazon EKS) cluster. The company must ensure that Kubernetes service accounts in the EKS
cluster have secure and granular access to specific AWS resources by using IAM roles for service accounts (IRSA).

Which combination of solutions will meet these requirements? (Choose two.)

A. Create an IAM policy that defines the required permissions Attach the policy directly to the IAM role of the EKS nodes.
B. Implement network policies within the EKS cluster to prevent Kubernetes service accounts from accessing specific AWS services.
C. Modify the EKS cluster's IAM role to include permissions for each Kubernetes service account. Ensure a one-to-one mapping between IAM roles and Kubernetes roles.
D. Define an IAM role that includes the necessary permissions. Annotate the Kubernetes service accounts with the Amazon ResourceName (ARN) of the IAM role. Most Voted
E. Set up a trust relationship between the IAM roles for the service accounts and an OpenID Connect (OIDC) identity provider. Most Voted

ans:

Why Answer D is Correct:
Granular IAM permissions: Creating an IAM role with specific permissions ensures that only the required AWS resources are accessible.
Service Account Annotation: The Kubernetes service account must be annotated with the IAM role ARN, so that AWS can map Kubernetes pods to the correct IAM role.

How it works:
Create an IAM Role with the necessary permissions.
Associate the IAM Role with a Kubernetes service account by adding an annotation:

apiVersion: v1
kind: ServiceAccount
metadata:
  name: my-service-account
  namespace: my-namespace
  annotations:
    eks.amazonaws.com/role-arn: arn:aws:iam::<account-id>:role/<IAM-Role-Name>

Why Answer E is Correct:
OIDC (OpenID Connect) Trust Relationship: Amazon EKS uses OIDC as an identity provider to allow Kubernetes service accounts to assume IAM roles securely.
Authentication Mechanism: AWS IAM needs a way to verify that a pod is associated with a specific Kubernetes service account, and it does
this using OIDC-based authentication.
How it works:
Enable OIDC for the EKS Cluster using:
eksctl utils associate-iam-oidc-provider --cluster <CLUSTER_NAME> --approve
Set up a trust policy that allows the IAM role to be assumed by a Kubernetes service account:
{
  "Effect": "Allow",
  "Principal": {
    "Federated": "arn:aws:iam::<account-id>:oidc-provider/<EKS_OIDC_PROVIDER>"
  },
  "Action": "sts:AssumeRoleWithWebIdentity",
  "Condition": {
    "StringEquals": {
      "<EKS_OIDC_PROVIDER>:sub": "system:serviceaccount:<namespace>:<service-account-name>"
    }
  }
}
Why the Other Answers are Incorrect:
❌ A. Attach IAM policy directly to the IAM role of the EKS nodes.
This grants broad permissions to the entire EKS node instead of specific Kubernetes service accounts, which is not secure or granular.
The goal of IRSA is fine-grained access control for service accounts, not node-wide access.
❌ B. Implement network policies within the EKS cluster to prevent Kubernetes service accounts from accessing specific AWS services.
Network policies control traffic between pods, not IAM permissions for AWS resources.
This does not address the requirement of granting specific permissions to AWS services.
❌ C. Modify the EKS cluster's IAM role to include permissions for each Kubernetes service account.
The EKS cluster IAM role is meant for managing the cluster itself (control plane), not for granting specific AWS access to Kubernetes service accounts.
This approach does not provide the necessary granularity at the service account level.


---------------------


A company has migrated several applications to AWS in the past 3 months. The company wants to know the breakdown of costs for 
each of these applications. The company wants to receive a regular report that includes this information.

Which solution will meet these requirements MOST cost-effectively?

A. Use AWS Budgets to download data for the past 3 months into a .csv file. Look up the desired information.
B. Load AWS Cost and Usage Reports into an Amazon RDS DB instance. Run SQL queries to get the desired information.
C. Tag all the AWS resources with a key for cost and a value of the application's name. Activate cost allocation tags. Use Cost Explorer to 
get the desired information. Most Voted
D. Tag all the AWS resources with a key for cost and a value of the application's name. Use the AWS Billing and Cost Management console todownload bills
for the past 3 months. Look up the desired information.

Why Other Options Are Incorrect:
❌ A. Use AWS Budgets to download data for the past 3 months into a .csv file. Look up the desired information.
AWS Budgets is useful for setting spending limits but not ideal for cost breakdowns by application.
Does not provide a detailed breakdown of past application costs efficiently.
❌ B. Load AWS Cost and Usage Reports into an Amazon RDS DB instance. Run SQL queries to get the desired information.
Expensive and complex because it requires setting up an RDS database and running SQL queries.
Unnecessary overhead when Cost Explorer already provides the required insights.
❌ D. Use the AWS Billing and Cost Management console to download bills for the past 3 months. Look up the desired information.
AWS bills are detailed but not easily categorized per application without cost allocation tags.
Manual process requiring more effort compared to Cost Explorer's automated reports.
Final Answer:
✅ C. Tag resources with an application name, activate cost allocation tags, and use AWS Cost Explorer.
This automated, cost-effective, and scalable solution allows the company to track and analyze costs easily for each application. 🚀
